<section id="shape" class="sheet section">
  <div class="section-heading">
    <p class="section-kicker">Why this exists</p>
    <h2>A small contract that scales from one file to many</h2>
  </div>
  <div class="two-up">
    <div>
      <p>
        The convention works because it keeps the machine-readable part tiny and pushes the subtle guidance into normal Markdown.
        This standard keeps that shape: frontmatter for structure, prose for judgment, and extra files only when the translation surface actually splits.
      </p>
      <p>
        The result is easy to author in a repository, easy to review in pull requests, and easy to validate with JSON Schema.
      </p>
    </div>
    <aside class="callout">
      <p class="callout-label">Directory shape</p>
      <pre><code>L10N.md
examples/
  app/
    L10N.md
    L10N/
      es.md
      ja.md
schemas/
  v1/</code></pre>
    </aside>
  </div>
</section>

<section id="documents" class="sheet section">
  <div class="section-heading">
    <p class="section-kicker">Document types</p>
    <h2>Three document shapes, one mental model</h2>
  </div>
  <div class="card-grid">
    <article class="card">
      <h3>Root `L10N.md`</h3>
      <p>Defines repository-wide context such as source language, tone, formatting rules, and brand terminology.</p>
      <p><a href="/L10N.md">Read the canonical example</a></p>
    </article>
    <article class="card">
      <h3>Scoped `L10N.md`</h3>
      <p>Lives inside a product or package directory and adds workflow settings like sources, validation strategy, target path, and target locales.</p>
      <p><a href="/examples/app/L10N.md">Read the scoped example</a></p>
    </article>
    <article class="card">
      <h3>`L10N/&lt;locale&gt;.md`</h3>
      <p>Captures language-specific guidance that should not leak into every locale, such as terminology preferences or layout constraints.</p>
      <p><a href="/examples/app/L10N/es.md">Read a locale overlay</a></p>
    </article>
  </div>

